Root cause is in `scripts/build.js` on Windows:

- It calls `spawnSync("bunx.cmd", ["--bun", ...])`.
- In this job, Node 22 on `windows-latest` fails with `Error: spawnSync bunx.cmd EINVAL` during `bun run build`.
- This is the failing point shown in the logs (`spawnargs: [ '--bun', 'electron-vite', 'build' ]`), so the release fails before packaging.

### Fix (recommended)
Avoid invoking `bunx.cmd` directly on Windows. Execute through Bun itself (or through a shell), which is more reliable in GitHub Actions Windows runners.

Update `scripts/build.js`:

```js
import { existsSync } from "node:fs";
import { spawnSync } from "node:child_process";

function run(args) {
  const result = spawnSync("bun", ["x", "--bun", ...args], {
    stdio: "inherit",
    shell: process.platform === "win32", // important for Windows runner resolution
  });
  if (result.error) throw result.error;
  if (result.status !== 0) process.exit(result.status ?? 1);
}

if (existsSync("electron/main.ts")) {
  run(["electron-vite", "build"]);
  const copy = spawnSync(process.execPath, ["scripts/copy-template.js"], { stdio: "inherit" });
  if (copy.error) throw copy.error;
  if (copy.status !== 0) process.exit(copy.status ?? 1);
} else {
  run(["vite", "build"]);
}
```

### Why this works
- `bun x ...` avoids direct `.cmd` process invocation edge cases.
- `shell: true` on Windows helps command resolution on hosted runners where direct `spawnSync("bunx.cmd")` can throw `EINVAL`.

### Optional hardening
If you want to stay with `bunx`, use explicit shell invocation on Windows:

```js
const result = process.platform === "win32"
  ? spawnSync("cmd.exe", ["/d", "/s", "/c", "bunx --bun " + args.join(" ")], { stdio: "inherit" })
  : spawnSync("bunx", ["--bun", ...args], { stdio: "inherit" });
```

