## Cause

`git rev-parse HEAD` fails when the repo has a `.git` folder but **no commits yet**, so `HEAD` does not point to any revision.

That happens during Pipper onboarding in `%APPDATA%\pipper\active`:

1. `git init` runs and creates `.git`
2. The initial `git commit` fails (or never runs)
3. Later, Pipper calls `git rev-parse HEAD` to write `installation.json` → crash

Common reasons the initial commit fails on Windows:

- First run partially completed (`.git` exists, no commit)
- `git commit` was run via shell with fragile quoting on Windows
- Git was not fully working yet when commit ran (now mitigated by install order)

After a failed run, Pipper sees `.git` already exists and **skips** re-initializing, but still calls `git rev-parse HEAD` — so the error persists on retry.

## Fix (in code)

I updated `initializeWorkspaces` to:

- Detect repos with `.git` but no `HEAD`
- Repair them by `git add -A` + `git commit` (or `--allow-empty` as fallback)
- Use `execFile` with argument arrays instead of shell strings (more reliable on Windows)

## If you're stuck right now (manual recovery)

In PowerShell:

```powershell
cd $env:APPDATA\pipper\active
git add -A
git -c user.name=Pipper -c user.email=pipper@internal commit -m "Initial commit"
```

If that says "nothing to commit":

```powershell
git -c user.name=Pipper -c user.email=pipper@internal commit --allow-empty -m "Initial commit"
```

Then restart Pipper and run onboarding again.

Or delete the whole library and start fresh:

```powershell
Remove-Item -Recurse -Force $env:APPDATA\pipper
```

Ship a new Windows build with this fix so new users do not hit it.

